      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 4,\n  \"summary\": \"The Iter-4 slot-conflict guard is structurally correct: role validation runs before any storage or conflict-check path, the 409 bodies expose only provider names (no credentials), and the removal of the `body.role != PRIMARY_ROLE` guard correctly extends coverage to primary-slot collisions rather than opening a bypass. One acknowledged TOCTOU race on concurrent attaches and one cosmetic `None`-coercion risk are the only outstanding issues. No blocking findings.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"providers.py:524-595\",\n      \"issue\": \"TOCTOU: `current` is snapshotted outside `update_host`'s lock. Two concurrent POST `/{name}/attach` requests for different providers but the same role both read the pre-conflict state, both pass the occupant check at line 585, and the last write wins — silently clobbering the first attach. The code itself acknowledges this as W3 at lines 566-571 and defers to a follow-up, but the race is real and can corrupt the attachment list on concurrent GUI interactions.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Push the conflict check inside the `updater` closure passed to `update_host` so it runs inside whatever write-lock that function holds. If `update_host` is not yet locking, add a per-agent async lock (e.g. `asyncio.Lock` keyed on `agent_key`) wrapping the read-check-write sequence in the route handler.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"providers.py:585-593\",\n      \"issue\": \"`_attachment_name(occupant)` can return `None` (line 390) if the occupant dict has no `name` key. `None != name` evaluates True (triggering the 409), and then `{_attachment_name(occupant)!r}` renders as `None` in the user-visible detail string rather than the real provider name.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Guard with `occ_name = _attachment_name(occupant); if occ_name is not None and occ_name != name:` and use `occ_name` in the detail string. In practice `normalize()` ensures dicts always carry a `name`, so this is cosmetic but worth closing.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"providers.py:537-543\",\n      \"issue\": \"`existing_role!r` in the same-provider-different-role 409 message can render as `''` (empty string) for legacy records that `normalize()` migrated with an empty role when a second string entry was encountered (provider_attachments.py:88-91). The message `with role ''` is truthful but confusing — it implies a valid known state that doesn't match VALID_ROLES.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Replace empty-role display with a fallback: `existing_role or '(unset)'` in the detail f-string. Also consider whether a stored empty role should be normalised away or rejected eagerly on read rather than surfaced in an error path.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Move the slot-conflict check and idempotent check inside the `update_host` updater closure to make the read-check-write atomic (#615 follow-up already tracked at line 569).\",\n    \"Add a null guard around `_attachment_name(occupant)` at line 593 before formatting the 409 detail string.\",\n    \"Consider structured 409 bodies (already noted as W4 in code at line 573-575) — the current prose string requires the frontend to parse provider names out of natural language, which is fragile.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 2,\n    \"domain\": \"provider-attachment API / GUI routes\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
